ead in your picture, and calculate the norm of the image \gradients. Create a binary picture where black (0) indicates high gradient \value at that point and white (1) indicates low gradient value. You should \decide your own threshold for low and high gradient values. Save the image. \Do this for both JPEG and TIFF images. \\>", "Text"]}, Open  ]],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell["Useful Classes and Libraries", "Subsection"],Cell["\<\You can use the following libraries to make things easier:    * Matrix Class (from Sinzinger) - reads images (using ImageMagick) and \allows for easy access and manipulation    * ImageMagick - allows for image I/O\\>", "Text"]}, Open  ]],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell["Solution", "Subsection"],Cell["\<\Part of the solution is the example image.cpp and image.hpp \produced by Eric Sinzinger.  This library requires expansion.  The new \functions necessary to impliment a gradient is differentiation.  This \differentiation can be accomplished via convolution.  Although there may be a \fast differential as well.  \\>", "Text"],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell["By Convolution:", "Subsubsection"],Cell[TextData[{  "The essessence of computing the gradient by convolution is :\n\t- Let V be \the matrix be worked on\n\t- Construct 2 copies of V ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`\((V\_r\ and\ V\_c)\)\)]],  "\n\t- For each row in ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_r\)]],  " convolute the row with ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`h = \((\(-1\), 0, 1)\)\^T\)]],  "\n\t- For each column in ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_c\)]],  " convolute the row with ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`h = \((\(-1\), 0, 1)\)\^T\)]],  "\n\t- Square each element in ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_r\ and\ V\_c\)]],  " .\n\t- Take the sum of the new ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_r\)]],  " and ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_c\)]],  " : ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_a = V\_r\^2 + V\_c\^2\)]],  "\n\t- Take the square root of each element in ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_a\)]],  " : ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_a = \@V\_a\)]],  "\n\t- Return ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`V\_a\)]],  " for it is the gradient.  \n\t"}], "Text"],Cell[TextData[{  "This seems simple, but the convolution for the row or column is an order \",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`n\^2\)]],  " algorithm:\nlet x be of length n\nlet h be of length m \nlet x be the \row/column vector\nlet h be the convoluting vector\n\t-for each element n: 0\\[LessEqual]i\[LessEqual]n\n\t\t* total = 0\n\t\t* for each element in k: 0\\[LessEqual]k\[LessEqual]m\n\t\t\ttotal += ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`x\_i*h\_\(m - k\)\)]],  "\n\t\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`x\_i = total\)]],  "\n"}], "Text"],Cell[TextData[{  "Notice that this requires a nested loop ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`\((O(n\^2))\)\)]],  ".  The is done for each row and column.  Thus making the algorithm ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`O(n\^2\[Times]m\^2)\)]],  ", where n and m are the row and column sizes.  This is a bit much.    "}], "Text"]}, Open  ]],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell["By fast method", "Subsubsection"],Cell[TextData[{  "Notice that the short form of the Central-Difference Approximation is \defined:\n\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`f\_i' = \(f\_\(i + 1\) - f\_\(i - 1\)\)\/\(2  h\) +           O(h)\)]],  "\n\twhere h is the approximation error operand.  Here h=1 thus\n\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`f\_i' = \(f\_\(i + 1\) - f\_\(i - 1\)\)\/2\)]],  "\nThere for each element can be calculated:"}], "Text"],Cell[TextData[{  "Let x be the row/ column vector of length n\nfor each element in x: \n\tif \0<i<n-1\n\t\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`y\_i = \((x\_\(i + 1\) - x\_\(i - 1\))\)\/2\)]],  "\n\tif i=0\n\t\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`y\_i = \(x\_\(i + 1\) - x\_i\)\/2\)]],  "\n\tif i=n\n\t\t",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`y\_i = \(x\_i - x\_\(i - 1\)\)\/2\)]]}], "Text"],Cell[TextData[{  "This calculation is order ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`\((O \((n)\))\)\)]],  ".  Obviously this is significantly faster than ",  Cell[BoxData[      \(TraditionalForm\`O(n\^2)\)]],  ".  "}], "Text"],Cell["\<\Irregardless, the differentiation needs to be available for row and \column operations.\\>", "Text"]}, Open  ]]}, Open  ]]}, Open  ]]}, Open  ]]},FrontEndVersion->"4.1 for Macintosh",ScreenRectangle->{{0, 1024}, {0, 746}},WindowSize->{655, 519},WindowMargins->{{96, Automatic}, {Automatic, 42}},PrintingCopies->1,PrintingPageRange->{1, Automatic},MacintoshSystemPageSetup->"\<\00<0004/0B`000002n88o?mooh<<H`Ui0fL5:0?l0080004/0B`000000]P2:0010000I00000400`<300000Gd000400AQ3N/0000000000060801T1T0000000000000000000004000000000000000000000\>"](*******************************************************************Cached data follows.  If you edit this Notebook file directly, notusing Mathematica, you must remove the line containing CacheID atthe top of  the file.  The cache data will then be recreated whenyou save this file from within Mathematica.*******************************************************************)(*CellTagsOutlineCellTagsIndex->{}*)(*CellTagsIndexCellTagsIndex->{}*)(*NotebookFileOutlineNotebook[{Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell[1727, 52, 41, 0, 108, "Title"],Cell[1771, 54, 36, 0, 61, "Subtitle"],Cell[1810, 56, 39, 0, 53, "Subsubtitle"],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell[1874, 60, 53, 3, 80, "Section"],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell[1952, 67, 33, 0, 46, "Subsection"],Cell[1988, 69, 356, 6, 62, "Text"]}, Open  ]],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell[2381, 80, 50, 0, 46, "Subsection"],Cell[2434, 82, 243, 8, 110, "Text"]}, Open  ]],Cell[CellGroupData[{Cell[2714, 95, 30, 0, 46,